Categories: Structured Text Processing -> Semantic Parsing -> Table Synthesis
Text Generation -> Structured Text Generation -> Table
Definition:
In this task, we ask you to parse restaurant descriptions into a structured data table of key-value pairs. Here are the attributes (keys) and their examples values. You should preserve this order when creating the answer: 
 name: The Eagle,... 
 eatType: restaurant, coffee shop,... 
 food: French, Italian,... 
 priceRange: cheap, expensive,... 
 customerRating: 1 of 5 (low), 4 of 5 (high) 
 area: riverside, city center, ... 
 familyFriendly: Yes / No 
 near: Panda Express,...
 The output table may contain all or only some of the attributes but must not contain unlisted attributes. For the output to be considered correct, it also must parse all of the attributes existant in the input sentence; in other words, incomplete parsing would be considered incorrect.

Positive Examples.input: Aromi is an English restaurant in the city centre.
Positive Examples.explanation: The output correctly parses all the parseable attributes in the input, no more, no less.

Positive Examples.input: The Rice Boat is a cheap Indian restaurant in the center of the city near Express by Holiday Inn. It is family friendly and has the highest customer rating.
Positive Examples.output: name[The Rice Boat], food[Indian], priceRange[cheap], customer rating[5 out of 5], area[city centre], familyFriendly[yes], near[Express by Holiday Inn]
Positive Examples.explanation: The output data table contains all the correct attributes and values from the input. All the attributes are as listed in the instruction; there are no made-up attributes.

Negative Examples.input: Blue Spice is a coffee shop located by the riverside, near Avalon. Its prices are over £30. Its customer ratings are 5 out of 5.
Negative Examples.output: name[Blue Spice], eatType[pub], priceRange[more than £30], customer rating[5 out of 5], area[Boston], familyFriendly[yes], near[Avalon]
Negative Examples.explanation: Incorrect Values: The values for some of the attributes are incorrect e.g. "pub" and "Boston".

Negative Examples.input: The Waterman is an expensive family-friendly Japanese restaurant with average customer rating in riverside
Negative Examples.output: name[The Waterman], customer rating[average], area[riverside], familyFriendly[yes]
Negative Examples.explanation: Incomplete Parsing: While the output correctly parses various attributes, it leaves out some parseable attributes such as "food[Japanese]" and "priceRange[expensive]"

Negative Examples.input: The Rice Boat is a cheap Indian restaurant in the center of the city near Express by Holiday Inn. It is family friendly and has the highest customer rating.
Negative Examples.output: name[The Rice Boat], type[cheap Indian restaurant], food[Indian], priceRange[cheap], customer rating[5 out of 5], area[city centre], familyFriendly[yes], near[Express by Holiday Inn]
Negative Examples.explanation: Incorrect Attributes: While most of the attributes were parsed correctly, "type[cheap Indian restaurant]" is a made-up attribute and therefore the output is considered incorrect.
